Start by figuring out if there are any like terms in the expression. Remember that if the terms have different exponents then the terms are not like terms. For example, 3ùë•3x and 5ùë•25x2 are not like terms.

STEP: Gather the like terms
[‚àí2 points ‚áí 0 / 2 points left]

The expression in the question has four terms. They are not all like terms: terms with different exponents are not like terms. For example, 2ùëì22f2 and 2ùëì2f are not like terms because 2ùëì22f2 has an exponent of 22 while 2ùëì2f has an exponent of 11.

However, there are some like terms: 9ùëì29f2 and 2ùëì22f2 are like terms, and they can be added together.

In this expression, the like terms are spread out in the expression (not next to each other). Before collecting like terms it is a good idea to write the expression so that the like terms are next to each other. In other words, put the terms in order. It is normal to write the terms with the largest exponents first.

==2ùëì+1+9ùëì2+2ùëì29ùëì2+2ùëì2+2ùëì+111ùëì2+2ùëì+1(order terms)(collect like terms)2f+1+9f2+2f2=9f2+2f2+2f+1(order terms)=11f2+2f+1(collect like terms)

Remember that when you collect like terms you just add the coefficients of the like terms.

The correct final answer is 11ùëì2+2ùëì+111f2+2f+1.
